{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_start","contentIndex":1,"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on my review of the arbitration record and admitted evidence, I have analyzed the case thoroughly. The key issue is whether Clavicular made a credible announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy during the specified window.\n\nThe record shows:\n1. The Polymarket market resolved Yes after multiple dispute rounds\n2. Forbes reported the dispute centered on \"a streamer who told his audience he had gotten a girl pregnant\"\n3. The Domahhhh thread confirms Clavicular \"claimed/joked that he got a girl pregnant\" \n4. The KickChamp post shows a viral claim about a girlfriend pregnancy with 15.5M+ views\n5. However, the record lacks the original VOD, transcript, or direct statement from Clavicular\n6. Multiple sources describe the statement as ambiguous, vague, and potentially a joke\n7. The biological timeline (10 days) is flagged as medically implausible\n\nThe critical missing piece is the primary source - the actual words spoken by Clavicular in their original context. While there's evidence that some pregnancy-related statement circulated, the record consistently undermines its credibility through descriptions like \"claimed/joked,\" \"vague,\" \"no proof,\" and biological implausibility.\n\nUnder the preponderance standard, the plaintiff has not met the burden of showing that a credible announcement occurred. The evidence points more strongly toward viral rumor and ambiguous streamer content than a qualifying credible announcement under the market rule."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_0d2c","name":"mcp","arguments":{},"partialArgs":"","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"t